<hl>
<seg id=1> US admits that aerial bombardments killed several hundred Iraqi civilians.  One British journalist said that bombs hit non-military targets. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News agency, Washington, February 13th -The White House admitted on February 13th that Alliance planes bombing Baghdad, the capital of Iraq, caused the deaths of several hundred Iraqi civilians, but insisted that the Alliance hit only military targets. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The White House Speaker Fitswalter said that the US government regards this as " a true tragedy". </seg>
<seg id=4> However, he condemned Iraqi President Saddam Hussein for putting civilians into military targets, and placing them in danger. </seg>
<seg id=5> He said that the US claims that the target they hit was an Iraqi military command and control center. </seg>
<seg id=6> This area "looked like it was painted to disguise it in order that it might avoid detection, but the evidence shows that it was a military target". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Xinhua News agency, London, February 13th - The BBC correspondent Bowin in Baghdad, the Iraqi capital, said on February 13th that, there was no evidence showing that the underground bunkers that the US hit were disguised military installations". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Bowin's report on the BBC news broadcast against the US governments claim that the bunker hit was a disguised military target. </seg>
<seg id=9> Bowin reported from the site of the destroyed bunker that about 400 civilians lost their lives. </seg>
</p>
